Process called "mips64_mprotect" takes addr as Integer, len as Integer, prot as Integer returns Integer:
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_MPROTECT(), addr, len, prot)
End Process

Process called "mips64_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return mips64_syscall_1(mips64_SYS_BRK(), addr)
End Process

Process called "mips64_execve" takes filename as Integer, argv as Integer, envp as Integer returns Integer:
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_EXECVE(), filename, argv, envp)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
66-PROC DISPATCHER API: syscall_<name> wrappers
============================================================================
These provide the canonical syscall_<name> entries required by the
assembly/syscall.runa dispatcher's 66-proc API surface (see
bootstrap/v0.0.8.5/docs/dev/designs/P2-B-cross-platform-threading-syscalls-design.md
Section "Per-platform syscall inventory" line 197).  They route through
the same syscall_N inline-asm thunks declared above; they are intentionally
thin so the dispatcher contract is uniform across all 18 platforms.
:End Note

Process called "mips64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_read(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5000 (SYS_READ).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_read = 5000.
    Returns number of bytes read, 0 at EOF, or negative errno on error
    (n64 returns -errno in $v0 with $a3=1 on the kernel side; the kernel
    ABI shim in syscall_N converts to a Linux-style signed return).
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_READ(), fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_write(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5001 (SYS_WRITE).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_write = 5001.
    Returns number of bytes written or negative errno on error.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_WRITE(), fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_open(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5002 (SYS_OPEN).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_open = 5002.
    MIPS64 still exposes a legacy mips64_open(2) syscall (unlike arm64/riscv which
    removed it in favour of openat-only).  Returns new file descriptor or
    negative errno on error.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_OPEN(), filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_close(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5003 (SYS_CLOSE).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_close = 5003.
    Returns 0 on success or negative errno on error.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_1(mips64_SYS_CLOSE(), fd)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_exit(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5058 (SYS_EXIT).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_exit = 5058.
    Terminates the current thread only.  Returns nothing on success
    (process is gone) but the API returns -1 / -errno on failure
    (e.g. kernel rejects an unmappable status value).
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_1(mips64_SYS_EXIT(), status)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_brk(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5012 (SYS_BRK).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_brk = 5012.
    Adjusts the program break (end of the data segment).  Returns the
    new break (which may differ from the requested addr if the kernel
    caps it) or -ENOMEM (negative) on failure.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_1(mips64_SYS_BRK(), addr)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_mmap(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5009 (SYS_MMAP).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_mmap = 5009.
    MIPS64 uses mmap (not mmap2) because n64 has full 64-bit registers
    for the offset argument; no page-shift conversion needed (unlike o32).
    Returns the mapped address (positive) or -errno (negative) on failure.
    n64 has 6 argument registers ($a0-$a5), so all 6 mmap args fit.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_6(mips64_SYS_MMAP(), addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_munmap(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5011 (SYS_MUNMAP).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_munmap = 5011.
    Unmaps the page-aligned region [addr, addr+length).  Returns 0 on
    success or -EINVAL/-errno (negative) on failure.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_2(mips64_SYS_MUNMAP(), addr, length)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    mips64_fstat(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5005 (SYS_FSTAT).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_fstat = 5005.
    Writes the struct stat for the given fd into statbuf.  The MIPS64
    stat layout is the n64 ABI variant (64-bit time fields, 64-bit ino).
    Returns 0 on success or -errno on failure.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_2(mips64_SYS_FSTAT(), fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    lseek(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5008 (SYS_LSEEK).
    Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_lseek = 5008.
    Repositions the file offset of fd.  Returns the new absolute offset
    from the beginning of the file or -errno on failure.  n64 native
    64-bit registers cover the full off_t range without _llseek tricks.
    :End Note
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_LSEEK(), fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on Linux MIPS64 (n64).
    __NR_ioctl is 5015 (Linux MIPS n64 ABI, 5000-base; see
    arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h). Three-arg shape (fd, request,
    argp). The n64 ABI uses 8 argument registers ($a0-$a7) and 64-bit
    register widths, so all arguments pass cleanly in registers
    without the o32 register-pair fixups required for MIPS32.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling mips64_SYS_IOCTL() (returns 5015)
    and mips64_syscall_3(5015, fd, cmd, arg). The n64 syscall
    convention loads 5015 into v0 ($2), fd into $a0, cmd into $a1,
    arg into $a2, then syscall; v0 holds the result (or errno when
    a3=$7 is set, decoded inside mips64_syscall_3 to negative-errno).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in the kernel — one FD-table lookup and a driver
    vtable jump. The n64 register-only argument convention avoids
    any spill/reload cost for the small ioctl argument tuple.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The kernel validates fd against the FD table and dispatches cmd
    through file_operations.unlocked_ioctl. arg, if a pointer, is
    dereferenced by the kernel with the structure size implied by
    cmd; callers must size the buffer to match. The n64 a3 error
    flag is decoded inside mips64_syscall_3, so the integer returned
    here is already in the canonical "negative-errno on failure"
    form.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_IOCTL(), fd, cmd, arg)
End Process
